+
+Two additional hazards came out of this table. First, the Compare tab's scalar anchor is itself confusing: `validation_report.py` turns multi-document YAML into `observables[]` by taking the first non-zero scalar in `reference_values` (`ui/backend/services/validation_report.py:107-154`), while `audit_real_run_measurement.yaml` reports a selected failed point `u_centerline[y=0.3750]`. So the scalar Compare tab can compare a measured point at one y against a gold scalar chosen from another y unless the backend has already aligned it. Second, the page text claims v-centerline and primary-vortex support, but the gold contract explicitly says those are not corrected and not exercised (`knowledge/gold_standards/lid_driven_cavity.yaml:26-32`, `knowledge/gold_standards/lid_driven_cavity.yaml:47-56`). For a novice report, this is not just shallow; it can create false claims.
+
+## Step 4 findings — Contour / geometry consistency
+- **Specified path mismatch** — The prompt path `reports/lid_driven_cavity/phase5_renders/` does not exist in this checkout. The actual LDC render path is `reports/phase5_renders/lid_driven_cavity/20260421T082340Z/`, with a manifest at `reports/phase5_renders/lid_driven_cavity/runs/audit_real_run.json`. This should become a finding because a student or Claude patcher following old paths will think renders are missing.
+- **`reports/phase5_renders/lid_driven_cavity/20260421T082340Z/contour_u_magnitude.png`** — This is the strongest current visual. It is recognizable as a square cavity: axes are `x/L`, `y/L`, aspect is visually square, and streamlines show a clockwise primary vortex near the upper-right half. The script enforces equal aspect and labels axes/colorbar (`scripts/render_case_report.py:511-520`). However, it lacks the novice callouts the user asked for: no "moving lid y=1, U=1 →" annotation, no primary vortex center label, no bottom-corner secondary-vortex labels, no Ghia side-by-side figure, no scale note explaining the colorbar is `|U|/U_lid`. It supports the mental image better than earlier visual-only assets, but it is not yet a teaching figure.
+- **`reports/phase5_renders/lid_driven_cavity/20260421T082340Z/profile_u_centerline.png`** — This is not a geometry/contour image; it is a useful profile comparison. It shows a blue sim curve and red Ghia markers, but the citation text at the bottom is truncated and a novice may not know why y=0.75/0.8125 deviations matter. It should be moved into Compare tab with explanatory labels.
+- **`reports/phase5_renders/lid_driven_cavity/20260421T082340Z/pointwise_deviation.png`** — This is the best existing error visualization. It shows 11/17 pass and red bars around y=0.6875-0.8125. It answers "where is the disagreement?" but not "why does disagreement cluster there?" It also does not connect to geometry, so the student cannot map failed y positions to top shear layer / vortex-center movement without extra explanation.
+- **`reports/phase5_renders/lid_driven_cavity/20260421T082340Z/residuals.png`** — Useful convergence evidence, not a contour. It has Ux/Uy/p residuals and log scale. It supports "solver converged" but not "flow physics correct." The Run tab correctly warns that convergence does not equal correctness (`ui/frontend/src/pages/learn/LearnCaseDetailPage.tsx:1450-1454`).
+- **`ui/frontend/public/flow-fields/lid_driven_cavity/centerline_profiles.png`** — This is a literature/reference plot, not solver output. It includes both u and v Ghia curves, which is helpful, but the current harness only compares u. Because the Story page renders it under "Literature reference" (`ui/frontend/src/pages/learn/LearnCaseDetailPage.tsx:358-387`) and its caption names v as well (`ui/frontend/src/data/flowFields.ts:21-24`), I would assume v validation is available. That assumption is false today.
+- **`ui/frontend/public/flow-fields/lid_driven_cavity/stream_function.png`** — This looks like a square cavity and has top arrows, but its provenance says it is a tensor-product ansatz calibrated to Ghia centerline profiles, not full DNS (`ui/frontend/src/data/flowFields.ts:27-30`). Visually, it is more symmetric and centered than the actual OpenFOAM contour. As a student, I see two different "pictures" of the same flow: the synthetic ψ plot center looks around the cavity middle, while the actual contour's primary vortex is upper-right. The page needs to explicitly label this as pedagogical only and put the real contour next to it.
+- **Does the rendering look alien?** For LDC specifically, the current real contour does not look alien; it looks like a plausible square cavity. The issue is not gross geometry mismatch. The issue is insufficient annotation plus inconsistent visual hierarchy: synthetic literature/ansatz figures and real solver figures are separated, not side-by-side, and only the real contour reveals the main vortex shape described in `physics_intuition_zh` (`ui/frontend/src/data/learnCases.ts:136`).
+
+## Step 5 — Novice report stub
+Using only the current `/learn/lid_driven_cavity` page, I would write the following report stub:
+
+The lid-driven cavity is a canonical two-dimensional incompressible Navier-Stokes benchmark. The geometry is a square cavity. The top wall moves to the right with nondimensional velocity \(U=1\), while the other three walls are no-slip. The Reynolds number is defined as \(Re=UL/\nu\), and the page focuses on Re=100. At this Reynolds number the flow is laminar and steady, so the page recommends `simpleFoam`, a steady SIMPLE solver, instead of a transient PISO/PIMPLE run. The main physical picture is that the moving lid drags the upper fluid layer to the right, viscosity transfers momentum downward, and the closed side and bottom walls force the flow to recirculate. This creates a large clockwise primary vortex and small counter-rotating secondary vortices near the lower corners.
+
+For validation, the page uses Ghia, Ghia & Shin 1982 as the gold standard. The primary observable is the horizontal velocity along the vertical centerline \(x=0.5\). The simulated \(u/U_{lid}\) profile should be compared to Ghia's tabulated values at multiple \(y/L\) locations. The page says the comparison is important because matching this profile is the first proof that the solver, mesh, boundary conditions, and extraction path are reasonable. The real OpenFOAM report shows a contour with streamlines, a centerline profile plot, a pointwise deviation plot, and a residual convergence plot. The residuals decay to around \(10^{-5}\), so the numerical iteration appears converged. The profile plot indicates that many Ghia points are close, but the pointwise deviation plot reports only 11/17 points inside the 5% tolerance. Therefore I would describe the current result as partially matching Ghia, not a clean validation pass.
+
+【I don't know】The page does not give me a complete `blockMeshDict`, `0/U`, `0/p`, `fvSchemes`, or `fvSolution`, so I cannot reproduce the run from the page without inventing files. 【I don't know】The workflow says 40x40 cells and `nu=0.01`, but the report figure says 129x129 and the generator uses `convertToMeters 0.1` with `nu=0.001`; I do not know which setup belongs in my course report. 【I don't know】The observable card says v-centerline and primary-vortex location are supported, but the current Compare tab only gives me one scalar tolerance band and the gold YAML warns that v-centerline and vortex center are not corrected. I cannot honestly claim five validation dimensions. 【Page doesn't say】I do not know how to compute the stream function, vortex strength, secondary vortex positions, integrated kinetic energy, or wall shear stress. 【Page doesn't say】I do not know how to cite the synthetic stream-function image versus the real OpenFOAM contour, or why the synthetic picture looks more symmetric than the real contour. Because of these gaps, the report can describe the physical story and one u-centerline comparison, but it cannot yet be a full reproducibility/validation report.
+
